  "text": "To test the action of mouse IFN-␥ in vivo, C57BL/6 mice with a disruption of the IFN-␥ gene (IFN-␥ Ϫ/Ϫ ) (4) and wildtype C57BL/6 mice (IFN-␥ ϩ/ϩ ) were used. After immunization with MV, both IFN-␥ ϩ/ϩ and IFN-␥ Ϫ/Ϫ mice develop MVspecific CD4 T cells which proliferate well after in vitro stimulation (Table 1 ). CD4 T cells from both strains stimulate mainly the production of IgG2b (Fig. 1) and do not secrete IL-4 or IL-5 (Table 1) . Due to the disruption of the IFN-␥ gene, IFN-␥ Ϫ/Ϫ CD4 T cells do not secrete IFN-␥, in contrast to IFN-␥ ϩ/ϩ T cells. Wild-type C57BL/6 mice (IFN-␥ ϩ/ϩ ) are highly susceptible to MVE after depletion of CD8 T cells [CITATION_1] . The transfer of MV-specific CD4 T cells (IFN-␥ ϩ/ϩ ) protected IFN-␥ ϩ/ϩ mice depleted of CD8 T cells against disease (Fig.  2) . After transfer of MV-specific CD4 T cells (IFN-␥ Ϫ/Ϫ ), the same level of protection was observed. These data demonstrate that mouse IFN-␥ has no direct antiviral effect against MV in vitro and in vivo.",
